Trim the @pak choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways.

Trim and halve the @green beans{150%g}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}(grated) (or use a garlic press).

Zest half the @lime{1/2}(zested) then cut in half.

Add @water{300%ml} to a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting lid.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} then cover and bring to the boil on medium-high heat.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to its lowest setting.

Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat (covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat (no oil).

When the pan is hot, add the @Irish beef mince{250%g} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.
> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Add the pak choi (and a drizzle of @?oil{to taste} if necessary) and cook until softened, stirring occasionally, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the garlic, @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} and @chicken stock{1%sachet}.

Add @water{100%ml} then stir everything together.

Add the green beans and simmer, stirring frequently until the liquid has reduced by half and the green beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

When the beef is ready, stir through the @hoisin sauce{2%sachets} and @sugar{2%tsp}.

Add lime juice to taste.

Remove from the heat, taste and season with salt, pepper and sugar if necessary.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest.

Share the lime rice between #bowls{}.

Serve the hoisin beef on top.

Squeeze over any remaining lime.